It has a stainless slide, great sights, an aluminum frame which makes it light, and it is probably one of the smoothest guns I've owned.For anyone who's not familiar with this series from Taurus, it (also the PT92/99) is almost an exact copy of the Beretta 92 series..and basically one of the only high quality firearms Taurus makes. I've had 3 of these copies and have never had an issue with a single one. Taurus purchased a factory from Beretta years ago, kept all of the machines, tools, and employees. For a while they made 100% copies, but after a few years they switched the safety from slide mounted, to frame mounted. A lot of people, including myself think this change is absolutely for the best. Beretta has used the frame mount a few times for their limited edition handguns and it is most definitely easier to use.Comes with one 17 round mag, and the box I got with it. title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Model 915 9mm
postcontent: Smith & Wesson Model 915 9mm THIS OLD SCHOOL MODEL 915 IS BARELY USED IN GREAT CONDITION.  COMES WITH ONE MAGAZINE.  The Smith & Wesson Model 915 is a full-sized, 9×19mm Parabellum (9mm Luger), short-recoil-operated double-action/single action (DA/SA) semi-automatic pistols with a four inch barrel and an aluminum alloy frame and a carbon steel slide. The S&W Model 915 was produced from 1992-1994. The Model 915 was part of the "Value Series" pistols made by Smith and Wesson, and incorporated several features to cut the costs associated with manufacturing "3rd Generation" Smith and Wesson pistols.[1] The Model 915 was made with only one safety/decocker lever (left side) in order to save costs. The Model 915 was made with all-metal parts, while the follow-on Model 910 substituted a plastic rear sight, plastic recoil guide rod, and plastic magazine release button to further save on manufacturing expenses.[2] The earlier Model 915 also reportedly has a lug on the barrel and a corresponding cut in the slide for tighter lock up. The later 910 has no lug on the barrel, nor a slide cut, reportedly affecting its inherent accuracy compared to the earlier 915. Both models have a reputation as reliable and robust.[3] The Model 915 was sold with a 15 shot double-stack magazine.  Magazines for the 915 are the same overall design as those used in the 59XX-series pistols and are interchangeable.[4]
